title: For Sale:  NORWEGIAN m. 1914 Colt license Kongsberg Norwegian Colt 1911 .45 cal. 11.25mm
postcontent: Super original example of this classic military pistol. This was the first licensed copy of the Colt 1911 .45 pistol. Norway began production in their own factory after purchasing 728 pistols from the Colt factory between 1911 and 1917. During WW II, production of the pistol was continued under Nazi occupation up to 1945. This pistol is serial number 13825, designated model 1914, and manufactured in 1927, with all matching numbered small parts, including the distinctive extended slide stop. Finish is the original blue, possible arsenal refinished at one time. Grips are the original double diamond Norwegian grips said to be made of birch wood. RARE original Norwegian nickel magazine with correct black painted base. C&R eligible.

title: For Sale:  Know the Laws Before Posting
location: South Carolina, South Carolina, United States
postcontent: there has been a few firearms listed lately that can cause legal issues for those selling.  If you have questions or issues just go to the BATFE WEBSITE and read what's legal and what can get you prison time unknowingly to some if you.  1). Currently theres an AK pistol listed in the state that has a front handgrip on the rail.........illegal........don't believe go by the local BATFE office and show it and ask if they like it2). The word is intent.  If you have an AR15 pistol upper and an AR 15 lower listed in the same listing or separate listings, just because the upper and lower are not attached doesn't make it legal 3). Read what the legal barrel lengths are for rifles and shotguns.  I saw an AR 15 with an advertised 14.5" barrel stating the flash hider made it a legal 16".  Well the flash hider was screwed on only.  An extension making a barrel the legal length has to be either welded 50% or more around the circumference or blind pinned and welded4). If your hobby is building rifles (or any firearm) cheap to sell for a profit you are selling in violation of federal law.  Some people sell an awful lot of "custom" AR15's aka I assembled it in my garage.Keep this in mind, if the BATFE ever decides to start cracking down some of you will need to lawyer up.
